     when the user wants to modify a previously	stored land
     pattern. The chosen pattern is displayed in the display
     window according to the scale of the base map.

     3)	After choosing the options

     range --> locate,

     the user can use the mouse	to place the pattern in	the
     desired location.	A click	of the left mouse button will
     translate the pattern so that its origin now lies at the
     pointed location. The middle button is clicked to signify
     the direction in which the	pattern	has to be oriented after
     rotation. The right button	signals	the end	of the location
     process.

     4)	In its final position, the pattern overlayed on	a base
     map can be	stored in a digit format file by activating the
     store function and	typing a unique	filename when prompted
     for one.

LINE OF	SITE ANALYSIS
     The following steps should	be used	to determine the
     visibility	of landscape from a specified observer location
     on	a base map which gives elevation data for all grid cells.

     1)	The user chooses the overlay of	elevation data to be
     shown in the display window using the options overlay -->
     display --> perm/user --> elevation_overlay.

     2)	The line of sight application is activated by clicking on
     the main menu option los.

     3)	The user specifies the observer	location by either of the
     following two ways:

	     (i)  viewpt --> text : The	user is	then prompted for
	     the global	UTM coordinates	of the observer	location.

	     (ii)  viewpt --> mouse : The user specifies the
	     observer location by clicking the mouse at	the
	     desired spot on the displayed elevation overlay.

     4)	The user can specify the height	of the observer	(in
     metres) above the viewing point's elevation by using the
     option obs_elev. If omitted, a default value of 1.75m is
     assumed.

     5)	The user can specify the maximum distance (in metres)
     from the viewing point inside which the line of sight
     analysis will be performed	by choosing the	option max_dist.
     The grid cells outside this distance range	are coded with



