     '0'. If omitted, a	default	maximum	distance of 100	grid
     cells is assumed.

     6)	The user must specify the filename of the output grid
     cell overlay that will be produced	by the program.	 Upon
     choosing the option outmap, the user is prompted for a
     filename unique among overlays existing under the user's
     individual	mapset.	 If a duplicate	overlay	exists,	a warning
     is	given and if accepted the existing overlay will	be
     overwritten.

     7)	The execute option starts the program which generates an
     output map	on which the cells that	are visible from the
     observer's	location are marked with integer values	that
     represent a measure of the	vertical angle required	to see
     those cells.

TRAJECTORY ANALYSIS
     The following steps should	be used	to perform the trajectory
     analysis on a base	elevation map.

     1)	The user chooses a base	map to be shown	in the display
     window  using the options overlay --> display --> perm/user
     --> basemap.

     2)	The trajectory analysis	tool is	activated by clicking on
     the main menu option traj.

     3)	The user specifies the weapon location by either of the
     following two ways:

	     (i)  firingpt --> text :  The user	is then	prompted
	     for the global UTM	coordinates of the weapon
	     location.

	     (ii)  firingpt -->	mouse :	 The user specifies the
	     weapon location by	clicking the mouse at the desired
	     spot on the displayed elevation overlay.

     4)	The user can specify the height	of the weapon (in metres)
     above the viewing point's elevation by using the option
     gun_elev.

     5)	The user can specify the two azimuth angles indicating
     the horizontal angle range	of firing by using the option
     azimuth.

     6)	The user can specify the low and high veritcal angles (in
     degrees) of firing	by using the option altitude.

     6)	The user can specify the muzzle	velocity (metres/sec) by
     using the option velocity.



